Virtual Network + pfSense Lab

So I started out by creating a virtualized internal network in VirtualBox. The idea was to simulate a real internal subnet that I could use to practice networking and basic pentesting.

To do that, I set all the VMs to use an Internal Network in VirtualBox and named it LAB. This acts like a virtual switch so everything on that network can talk to each other but has no internet access by default.

The machines I used were:

Kali Linux (for scanning/testing)
Ubuntu (target machine)
Windows 10 (target machine)

Since this network doesn’t have DHCP I had to manually assign IP addresses to everything.

On Windows I did this through:

Control Panel → Network Settings → IPv4 config

On Ubuntu it was a bit different, I set the IP manually through the terminal.

Everything was put on the same subnet:

192.168.50.0/24

so all the machines could communicate with each other directly.

After that, I added a pfSense VM to act as a router.

The pfSense box had:

one adapter set to NAT (for internet access)
one adapter connected to the LAB internal network

Then I set the LAN IP on pfSense to:

192.168.50.1

That became the default gateway for the whole subnet.

Once pfSense was in place, I updated each machine to use it as the default route.

On Linux I did:

ip route add default via 192.168.50.1

and on Windows I set the gateway in the IPv4 settings.

At that point, traffic from the internal network was being routed through pfSense and out to the internet through NAT.

So by the end of it:

all machines could talk to each other on the internal network
the network was still isolated logically
but now had controlled internet access through pfSense

This basically gave me a small but realistic internal network setup that I can now use for things like scanning, service enumeration, and testing firewall rules.

